{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486857"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:47:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:47:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"192"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/192"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.26,0.13,0.02,0.58]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"192"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90830"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/192"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"192"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74893"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"237"},{"type":"tags","id":"1367"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"6628"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3949"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31128"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42024"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90830"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with an irregular superficial ulcer around his right medial malleolus that has been present for about three weeks. There is moderate pain in the ulcer, which is relieved with elevation of the leg. The patient has not been to see his General Practitioner for a number of years and takes no regular medications. On examination, the area around the lower leg and ulcer is a dark purple rusty colour (Image). His femoral pulses are of good volume and equal, and pedal pulses are strongly palpable. The ankle-brachial index in both legs is 1.0.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Skin grafts","Debridement of the ulcer and dress","Urgent vascular referral","Systemic oral antibiotics","Compression bandages with moist wound dressing"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe stem suggests a venous ulcer due to its location in the medial gaiter region, surrounding haemosiderin staining, and moderate pain that alleviates with elevation. The good arterial vascularity as evidenced by strong pedal pulses and normal ankle-brachial index reduces the likelihood of arterial malperfusion as the cause. A normal ankle-brachial index infers that there is no evidence of arterial obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAppropriate treatment at this stage would be \u003Cstrong\u003Ecompression bandages\u003C/strong\u003E to reduce venous engorgement and \u003Cstrong\u003Emoist wound dressing\u003C/strong\u003E to control exudate and encourage epithelial regrowth. The presence of peripheral arterial disease would be a contraindication to direct compression - but that is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkin grafting\u003C/strong\u003E might be appropriate if the wound does not respond to simple measures. There is no need for any \u003Cstrong\u003Eurgent vascular surgical opinion\u003C/strong\u003E and nor is any other form of intervention (such as \u003Cstrong\u003Edebridement \u003C/strong\u003Eor \u003Cstrong\u003Esystemic oral antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E) required as there are no apparent signs of infection or necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A chronic ulcer around the ankle is most likely to be venous in origin."],"references":["Lim CS, Baruah M, Bahia SS. Diagnosis and management of venous leg ulcers. BMJ 2018;362:k3115. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30108047/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74893"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"192"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15192"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15192"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7b54a9ce-9a68-4aff-9a5f-fd22db6ddbb0.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7b54a9ce-9a68-4aff-9a5f-fd22db6ddbb0.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":565}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74893"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T16:39:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T16:39:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"192"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90830"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroup